    en: "New York is an at-will employment state — an employer can generally fire an employee for any reason or no reason. But common-law decisions by the NY Court of Appeals (most prominently Murphy v. American Home Products, 1983) have created narrow exceptions. A discharge is wrongful when it violates (1) an express employment contract for a definite term, (2) an implied-in-fact contract arising from handbook promises or express policies, or (3) a specific statutory protection (discrimination, retaliation for whistleblowing, etc.). NY has NOT recognized a broad 'public policy' exception that other states adopt. Claims must fit within a narrower category. Remedies include reinstatement, back pay, and damages; fee-shifting applies for statutory claims."
